<DOC><DOCNO> ZF310-587-262 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 587 262</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Wall Street Journal  April 15 1991 pB1(W) pB1(E) 28 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Redistricting draws business to small firms.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Carlson, Eugene.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Small software consulting firms are taking advantage of therealignment of new electoral districts by providing computerservices and expertise.andP;  The districts are changed once every tenyears to conform to population shifts that have occurred in thepast decade.andP;  The old days of redrawing districts on maps withpencils have given way to computerized graphics, where entireblocks of the population can be moved from one district to thenext and the results totalled as requested.andP;  The redistricting hascreated considerable opportunity for software companies versed inthe art of geographic information systems (GISs), or computermapping with integrated with data.andP;  Sales of actual GIS softwareare also up, as companies with vested interests in thisrealignment of voting districts are willing to expend considerablemoney for in-house expertise.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Political IssuesGovernmentBusiness.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   The bizarre shape of politics. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>